<h1>@HI{{sou desu}} (appearance, looks like)</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<p>
<dl>
<li> @V2{{}} <strong>@HI{{sou desu}}</strong>
<li> @Aistem{{}} <strong>@HI{{sou desu}}</strong>
<li> @Anastem{{}} <strong>@HI{{sou desu}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

When the present state of something leads the speaker to presuppose an occurrence, the speaker uses this sentence
pattern to state it. The speaker is expressing a conjecture based on visual information and so this pattern
is only used when the speaker directly observes something. Furthermore, the conjecture concerns the future
state and so this sentence patten cannot refer to conjecture about a past state.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{now}}ni mo @KJ{{rain}}ga @KJ{{descend}}ri<strong>sou desu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    It lools like it will rain at any moment.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono@KJ{{fee^logic}}ha @KJ{{spicy}}<strong>sou desu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    This dish looks spicy.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{he^woman}}ha @KJ{{head}}ga yosa<strong>sou desu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    She seems to be bright.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono @KJ{{desk}}ha @KJ{{length^husband}}<strong>sou desu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    This desk looks strong and durable.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>


<h2> Notes </h2>

@HI{{ii}} becomes @HI{{yosa sou desu}} and @HI{{nai}} becomes @HI{{nasa sou desu}} in this sentence pattern.
<p></p>

Neither N + @HI{{sou desu}} nor N @HI{{da sou desu}} are permitted but N + @HI{{janasa sou desu}} is permitted.
<p></p>

@HI{{sou desu}} can be used as a @HI{{na}}-adjective in the form @HI{{souna}}.
<p></p>

